          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Louisville Ky</placeName>
                                        <date>May 25<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1853</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">B. H. Gotthelf</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="Envelope"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <placeName>Walnut St No 371</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <placeName>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>
                                        </placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p><placeName>Louisville, Ky.</placeName>
                                        <date>May 25, 1853</date>.</p>
                              <p>Most honored <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>:</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I regret with all my heart, that I had to delay my
                                        answer<lb/> to you so long, and even now, I am not in a
                                        position to write to you in<lb/> much detail as I should
                                        like. In the month before the last, I went to the<lb/>
                                        post-office, and after several inquiries, I received six
                                        numbers which<lb/> had not been delivered. Every one of them
                                        had had the address torn off<lb/> But who was it who had not
                                        received them? I, therefore, waited several more<lb/> weeks
                                        for the last number, and, several days later, upon receiving
                                        my<lb/> own, I found only three left over, but also without
                                        address. Since<lb/> I have acquired two new subscribers,
                                        whose names I shall write<lb/> below, I gave them two of
                                        these copies. Later, I saw nothing until<lb/> yesterday,
                                        when I again found five copies and two exemplars<lb/>
                                        “Obligation of the Sabbath” Of these five copies, only three
                                        had<lb/> addresses, namely, <persName>Israel
                                                  Hyman</persName>, <persName>L. Bach</persName>,
                                        and <persName>Sol. Simmons</persName>,<lb/> the last, as I
                                        have recently found out, is now in
                                                  <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>, then<lb/> I
                                        think I can transmit this copy to him. As I wrote to you
                                        in<lb/> that letter you have not yet received, the following
                                        have discontinued:—<lb/>
                                        <persName>Abraham Din Kelsfial</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Goldberg</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Mark</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Mark</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Rosenberg</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Sale</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Hy<lb/>man</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Zilberman</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Uhlman</persName>, <persName>E.
                                                  Bamberger</persName>, <persName>Moses
                                                  Lieberman</persName>, and<lb/> if I am not
                                        mistaken, <persName>J. Lieber</persName>. You see,
                                        therefore, that almost all<lb/> your subscribers here, while
                                        they do not look down upon your<lb/> periodical, hate to
                                        give up the $3. Since I received altogether five<lb/> copies
                                        which have not been called for, I cannot tell you in
                                        detail<lb/> up to the present moment. For the same reason, I
                                        have not yet collected<lb/> much. For I should very much
                                        like to see, the economical gentlemen<lb/> accepting the new
                                        copies before they pay for the old—and thus become
                                                  <add>?</add><lb/>......Believe me, dear
                                                  <persName>Mr. Leeser</persName> that I have taken
                                        a great deal of<lb/> trouble with these people, as much as
                                        you yourself would have taken, but<lb/> not I nor even our
                                        teacher <persName>Moses</persName> could change these
                                        people. As I<lb/> told you, I have two new
                                                  subscribers—<persName>B. Myer</persName>,
                                                  <placeName>Hodgensville, Ky.<lb/> Larue,
                                                  Ct.</placeName>, and <persName>S.
                                                  Oberndorfer</persName>, <placeName>3<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >rd</hi> St. between Market &amp;
                                                  Jefferson</placeName>.<lb/> Please send the new
                                        copies to their address. After receipt of the next
                                        issue<lb/> I shall unhesitatingly collect and send it to you
                                        as soon and as<lb/> much as possible. I should very much
                                        like to write some pleas<add>?</add><lb/> news to you, but
                                        the circumstances, as you will see, do not per<lb/>mit it.
                                        Perhaps in my next letter, I'll be able to do so. My<lb/>
                                        wife and children send kindest greetings. Your most
                                        devoted<lb/> servant and friend,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <persName role="author">B. H. Gotthelf</persName>
                              </p>
                    </body>
